<td valign="top">
<p><img height="300" width="237" src="http://www.edenhrconsulting.com/images/stories/eden-stick-figures/eden-health-safety.jpg" alt="eden-health-safety" style="float: right;" />Every pregnant woman must be risk assessed within the work place - It’s the law! Of course it’s also the right thing to do morally</p>
<p>You should assess the risks of each activity undertaken by your pregnant employee, and think about the “control measures” or actions you will undertake in order to minimise the risk.  On completion of the assessment and implemented control measures the risks should be low.  If there are medium or high risks, then the activities associated with the medium/high risk levels should be ceased, and if these activities are a large part of the employees role, she should be reassigned other duties during her pregnancy or suspended on health and safety grounds.</p>
<p>Maternity risk assessments are tailored to risks experienced by pregnant employees e.g. movement and posture, standing and sitting for long periods, manual handling (also considering the employee's return from maternity if she has a caesarean) etc.</p>
<p>Let Eden help you manage the assessment to ensure it’s done correctly and give you peace of mind.</p>
<p> </p></td>
